Class ImpreciseValue<T extends ImpreciseValue<T>>

java.lang.Object
java.lang.Number
com.rb.nonbiz.types.RBNumeric<T>
com.rb.nonbiz.types.ImpreciseValue<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:

Direct Known Subclasses:
Correlation, Epsilon, NonNegativeMultiplier, PositiveMultiplier, ZScore
public abstract class ImpreciseValue<T extends ImpreciseValue<T>>
extends RBNumeric<T>
A base class for creating typesafe versions of a Double, with two goals: tightening semantics, and making code easier to read.

It is somewhat like a C typedef, which Java lacks, except that subclasses may also add constructor preconditions.

An example is PositiveMultiplier: the name tells you that it's supposed to be used as a multiplier (not an offset for addition, not a dollar amount, etc.), and also that it is positive, not negative or zero.

This is like PreciseValue, but it doesn't carry one of the benefits of PreciseValue (namely, having a precise, BigDecimal value). However, like PreciseValue, it lets us have more clearly named comparison methods: val1.isLessThan(val2) is clearer than val1.compareTo(val2) < 0 More importantly, since Java doesn't allow typedefs, it gives us a general way to implement simple wrappers around a single double.

The name is a bit odd; 'imprecise' doesn't sound like a positive feature. However, it is a clear contrast to PreciseValue.

    • almostEquals

      public boolean almostEquals​(T other, Epsilon epsilon)
      Assuming it's possible to do so and not restricted by the generics mechanism (e.g. a comparison between Money and BuyQuantity), this will compare the BigDecimal values. There's a few cases where this is counterintuitive, e.g. buyQuantity(10).almostEquals(sellQuantity(10), 1e-8) is true. The upside is fewer conversions and fewer cases where we have an unexpected result because we forgot to do some conversion.
